    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-03T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-03T10:00:00-05:00" n="173"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d173">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.24/375: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-03T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 3, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>668. A member of the British Embassy has informed me in confidence that Soviet
                    officials have on several occasions expressed their resentment at the remarks
                    made in public by Lord Halifax several weeks ago in which he indicated that
                    Great Britain desired to prevent the shipment of certain commodities from the
                    United States to the Soviet Union on the ground that their ultimate destination
                    was Germany. He emphasized, however, that no formal protest has been made.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
